## Strengths (Why This Is Investable)

### 1. RBAC Is Now Implemented End-to-End ✅ (Previously: High Risk)
The most critical security gap from the Feb review is **resolved**. Endpoints across all domains (Catalog, CRM, Inventory, Core) now use `.HasPermission(Permissions.*)` with granular permission constants. Evidence: `src/Degmeda.B2B.Api/Endpoints/Crm/Orders/Cancel.cs` → `HasPermission(Permissions.CrmOrderCancel)`, `src/Degmeda.B2B.Api/Endpoints/Core/Tenants/GetById.cs` → `HasPermission(Permissions.CoreTenantRead)`, and consistently across endpoints. `PermissionProvider.GetForUserIdAsync` is fully implemented with role→permission mapping and is covered by tests (`PermissionProviderTests`).

### 2. CI/CD Pipeline Exists ✅ (Previously: High Risk)
Three GitHub Actions workflows now exist:
- `docker-publish.yml` — container build and push to GHCR
- `test-profiles.yml` — automated test execution
- `docs-check.yml` — documentation structure enforcement

This resolves the previous "zero automated protection against regressions" finding.

### 3. Integration Test Suite Is Meaningful ✅ (Previously: High Risk — Skeletal)
New test infrastructure includes:
- `Common.Testing` — shared test library (builders, fixtures)
- `AuthorizationPolicyIntegrationTests` — tests unauthenticated 401, Guest 403 on approve, Manager 200 on search, User 200 on warehouse read, User 403 on create supplier
- `ErrorContractIntegrationTests` — tests 500 on duplicate inventory rows, 404 on missing tenant
- `ProblemDetailsContractTests` — validation error contract tests
- 7 test projects total (up from 6 with addition of `Common.Testing`)

The test coverage now explicitly covers authorization policies and error contracts — two of the three highest-priority gaps from last review.

### 4. Session-Based Permission Distribution
`docs/archive/2026-03-04/frontend-session-permissions-guide.md` documents a move from JWT-claim-based permissions to session-response-based permissions (`POST /auth/sign-in`, `POST /auth/switch-tenant`, `GET /auth/session` all return `permissions[]` array). This is architecturally superior and decouples frontend from JWT token shape.

### 5. Architecture Is Genuinely Solid (Unchanged)
Clean Architecture with enforced layer boundaries (`tests/Degmeda.B2B.Architecture.Tests`), domain model reflecting real manufacturing complexity, multi-tenancy via EF Core Global Query Filters — all remain strong.

### 6. Documentation Culture Continues to Improve
13 accepted ADRs (up from 11). Two new since Feb: `2026-02-28-forgot-password-jwt-flow.md` and `2026-03-04-tenant-settings-ownership-model.md`. Task-indexed documentation (`docs/current/index-by-task.md`) updated. Backend-frontend contract updated with full permission endpoint matrix.

### 7. Soft Delete and Audit Trail Remain Baked In

